- Feedback saturation calls
    - format: one entry per chapter when first-pass extraction completes
    - entry shape:
        - what came out of this chapter
        - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - why those did not make it
        - decision: saturated | re-sweep needed

- Chapter 1: Front Matter (praise, title page, copyright, dedication, contents)
    - what came out: nothing
    - what didn't make the gate: not applicable. Bibliographic metadata, no teaching content.
    - why: structural front matter, not authorial argument or demonstration.
    - decision: saturated (vacuously, with zero skills)

- Chapter 2: Introduction (From Push to Pull)
    - what came out: three skills
        - pull-not-push-reroute: moment-to-moment application of the receiver-as-leverage reframing, used when the giver-inadequacy inventory is running.
        - engaging-is-not-accepting: separates the engage-skillfully decision from the take-the-feedback decision, dissolving the swallow-or-shut-out binary.
        - name-both-needs: names the simultaneous drives to learn and to be accepted as the diagnostic for outsized or delayed reactions.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the broad definition of feedback (any information about yourself): parent-context framing, no distinct receiver-side action.
        - the brief mechanical-to-managerial history of "feedback": context, not procedure.
        - feedback-seeking behavior research: empirical motivation for the book; the actual seeking procedure lives in chapter 12 (Get Going).
        - modeling effect (kids, direct reports): stakes-raising frame, not a receiver move.
        - "digging for ponies" disposition: aphorism that points at "First Understand" (chapter 5) where the actual technique is taught.
        - the three triggers themselves: previewed only; the chapter that develops them is chapter 1 (Three Triggers That Block Feedback) where they get their own skills.
    - why those did not make it: most of the intro establishes the lens and vocabulary that already live in _book.md, or signposts later chapters where the actual procedures get developed. Pulling skills here would either duplicate parent context or pre-empt material the book itself defers.
    - decision: saturated (3 skills)

- Chapter 3: 1. Three Triggers That Block Feedback
    - what came out: one skill
        - identify-which-trigger-is-firing: the chapter's framework-level meta-move. When triggered by feedback, name which of truth/relationship/identity (or which mix) is firing before applying any remedy. Folds in the smoke-alarm framing (triggered reaction is a map, not just an obstacle), since reading the alarm and categorizing among the three is a single move.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - separate appreciation, coaching, evaluation: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 4.
        - first understand: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 5.
        - see your blind spots: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 6.
        - don't switchtrack (disentangle what from who): previewed here but is the spine of chapter 7.
        - identify the relationship system: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 8.
        - learn how wiring and temperament affect your story: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 9.
        - dismantle distortions: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 10.
        - cultivate a growth identity: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 11.
    - why those did not make it: chapter 1 is a synopsis chapter. Each remedy under the three triggers is the title of a chapter that follows, and the deep treatment (specific moves, signals, failure modes, scenarios) lives there. Promoting a half-developed version here would either pre-empt material the book itself defers, or force a duplicate skill when the dedicated chapter is reached. The skills system is better served by leaving each per-trigger remedy for its own chapter and extracting only what is genuinely born in this chapter: the framework-level diagnostic that names the trigger before selecting any remedy.
    - decision: saturated (1 skill)

- Chapter 4: 2. Separate Appreciation, Coaching, and Evaluation
    - what came out: four skills
        - sort-the-kind: the chapter's meta-move. When "feedback" is on the table (giving, getting, asking), name which of the three kinds (appreciation / coaching / evaluation) is in play. The categorize-the-kind move is parallel to identify-which-trigger-is-firing (which categorizes the receiver's reaction); sort-the-kind categorizes the message itself.
        - diagnose-the-cross-transaction: the chapter's diagnostic for when feedback lands wrong despite good faith. Two patterns: want-vs.-got mismatch (April/Cody/Evelyn) and intent-vs.-hearing mismatch (the structural evaluative echo inside coaching, with Elsie). Folds in the structural "always evaluation in coaching" insight as the second pattern of mismatch.
        - negotiate-which-kind-you-need: the chapter's prescriptive remedy. Use the three alignment questions, name the kind you want out loud, ask the giver to name what they think they are giving, and surface explicit disagreement rather than absorb the wrong kind. Captures the chapter's bull-by-the-horns scripts.
        - settle-evaluation-first: the chapter's sequencing principle. Evaluation is structurally loud and drowns out coaching and appreciation; settle the where-do-I-stand question (or defer the rest) before trying to absorb the others. Folds in the "evaluative floor" point from "Evaluation Shortfalls" (silent evaluation creates the same stuck state as a loud unfavorable evaluation).
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the three qualities of meaningful appreciation (specific, in receivable form, authentic): cast as criteria for givers; the receiver-side analog (notice when received appreciation lacks one; ask for it in a form you can hear) was too thin a procedure on its own and is already covered by sort-the-kind plus negotiate-which-kind-you-need.
        - mutual appreciation deficit disorder (MADD): a relational dyad-level diagnosis; not a moment-of-receipt receiver action with its own signal and failure.
        - the always-evaluation-in-coaching structural insight: not its own skill; folded into diagnose-the-cross-transaction as the second mismatch pattern.
        - the "evaluative floor" / evaluation-shortfalls insight: not its own skill; folded into settle-evaluation-first because the silent-evaluation and loud-evaluation cases produce the same stuck state and call for the same sequencing remedy.
        - the Luke / America's Got Talent sidebar (entertainment-as-feedback): the receiver-side action is too situation-specific (mediated, public feedback with a third-party gallery) to generalize; structural insight already covered by sort-the-kind plus engaging-is-not-accepting.
    - why those did not make it: the giver-side guidance (appreciation qualities, MADD framing) is not the receiver focus the book frames itself around, and the receiver-side equivalents collapse into the four atomic moves above. The structural insights (always-evaluation-in-coaching, evaluative-floor) are real but each is most useful as a condition or pattern inside one of the four primary skills, not as its own atomic move. The Luke sidebar is illustrative of the categorize-the-kind move in a special case (mediated/public feedback) rather than a separate skill.
    - decision: saturated (4 skills)

- Chapter 5: 3. First Understand (Shift from "That's Wrong" to "Tell Me More")
    - what came out: five skills
        - catch-the-wrong-spotting: the chapter's spine move. Receiver-side recognition of the habitual wrong-spotting mode (listening with the question "what is wrong with this feedback") and the upstream switch that makes the rest of the chapter's understanding moves possible. Folds in the wrong-spotting catalogue (2+2=5, different-planet, used-to-be-right, etc.) and Paul's preparation mindset ("not to accept or reject, but first to understand").
        - spot-the-label: the surface-form pattern recognition move. Notice when feedback arrives as an evaluative label ("be more X," "you are too Y") that has high-definition meaning in the giver's head and almost no content in transit, and resist the auto-fill of your own meaning. The Adrianna/Nicholas "be more assertive" and the "be more affectionate" multiple-choice are the worked examples.
        - separate-data-from-interpretation: the chapter's "coming-from" move. Pull apart the giver's observed data from the interpretation they made of it, push past second-order interpretations offered as data, and watch your own confusion of the two. Captures the chapter's explicit decomposition (lines 1281-1341) and the Nicholas-pushing-Adrianna script.
        - clarify-where-its-going: the chapter's "going-to" move. Unifies coaching-clarification and evaluation-clarification under one move (when the feedback has a future, ask for it, in the right form for the kind), with the actionability test for coaching ("if I wanted to follow this, would I know how?") and the rip-cord question set for evaluation (consequences, expectations, what-now).
        - difference-spot-not-wrong-spot: the chapter's second-stage move. When you have understood and still disagree, ask what is different about your data and what is different about your interpretations rather than concluding one of you is wrong. Folds in the implicit-rules and heroes-and-villains material as the two specific interpretive-difference factors, and the ask-what's-right coda as the closing step.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the "understand before judging" disposition (lines 1153-1158, 1616-1619): folded into catch-the-wrong-spotting, where the disposition is the substrate the wrong-spotting catch installs.
        - ask-what's-right (lines 1536-1545): folded into difference-spot-not-wrong-spot as the closing coda; standalone it would be too thin (write a list) and the chapter explicitly cautions about right-spotting collapsing into wrong-spotting if treated alone.
        - when-you-still-disagree (lines 1551-1566): dropped because the move (be transparent about reactions while staying open and curious) is a tonal/script-level extension of engaging-is-not-accepting (already promoted in chapter 2), not a new structural diagnostic.
        - "why can't feedback just be objective" (lines 1572-1585): dropped as a frame the chapter argues for rather than a receiver action; the actionable corollary (treat all feedback as judgment-laden) is captured by separate-data-from-interpretation and sort-the-kind.
        - the Paul-and-Monisha conversation walk-through (lines 1591-1692): dropped as a standalone skill (it is the chapter's synthesis scene); used as the worked-example source for catch-the-wrong-spotting, spot-the-label, separate-data-from-interpretation, and difference-spot-not-wrong-spot.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter's argument is built as a linear flow of understanding moves (catch the wrong-spotting → spot the label → separate data from interpretation → clarify where it's going → shift to difference-spotting → ask what's right → sit with disagreement). Each major move along that flow earns a skill. The coda moves (ask-what's-right, when-you-still-disagree) are best treated as steps inside their parent skills rather than separate atomic moves, because by themselves they lack distinct signal and failure shapes that the parent does not already supply. The objective-feedback section is structural argumentation. The Paul/Monisha scene is a synthesis demonstration, useful as illustration but not its own move.
    - decision: saturated (5 skills)

- Chapter 6: 4. See Your Blind Spots (Discover How You Come Across)
    - what came out: five skills
        - use-your-reaction-as-blind-spot-alert: when feedback feels wrong and your mind builds a case against the giver (their agenda, their personality, their politics), treat the case-against-the-giver itself as the alarm that the feedback may be in your blind spot. The chapter is explicit that "looking harder" produces the same dismissal verdict, so the inversion is to substitute the blind-spot question for the agenda question.
        - ask-how-am-i-getting-in-my-own-way: replace the noncommittal eliciting questions ("any feedback?", "how am I doing?") with the chapter's specific phrasing, which names the desired honesty and narrows the topic to behavior with observable impact. The replacement is the move; the receive-side curiosity is the second half.
        - name-which-mirror-you-need: when taking feedback to a friend or partner for a second opinion, name out loud which kind of mirror you are asking for, honest or supportive. The default ask is implicitly supportive; the chapter validates both as legitimate and locates the trouble in conflation.
        - look-for-pattern-not-counterexample: invert the contradictory-evidence reflex. Look for consistency in two ways: (1) the same-behavior-different-interpretation table (shy/aloof, high-standards/hypercritical, outgoing/overbearing), and (2) "where have I heard this before?" Recurrence across time and source is the strongest receiver-side blind-spot evidence.
        - separate-impact-from-intent: when impact feedback contradicts self-perceived intent, hold both layers separately rather than collapsing into "I had good intentions so the impact wasn't real" or "the impact was bad so my intentions must have been worse than I knew." Folds in the leaky-face/tone/patterns substrate (others' impact data is your only access to behavior you can't see), the three amplifiers (emotional math, situation/character, impact/intent), and the inside-out change move (surface behavior change leaks if the underlying feeling stays intact).
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - The Gap Map itself (lines 1781-1808): parent frame for the chapter's atomic moves, analogous to the three-triggers frame in chapter 1; as a standalone skill the action would be "draw the map" with no observable signal of having drawn it.
        - Behavioral blind spots as a category (leaky face / leaky tone / leaky patterns, lines 1814-1880): folded into separate-impact-from-intent as the substrate that makes the impact-as-data move sensible. Not its own skill because the action ("notice that your face/tone/patterns are invisible to you") is purely descriptive without the impact-vs-intent move that converts the asymmetry into a procedure.
        - Emotional math (lines 1919-1934) and Situation versus Character (lines 1940-1947): folded into separate-impact-from-intent as two of the three amplifiers. As own skills the action ("notice when you are subtracting an emotion / explaining behavior by the situation") would not produce a distinct signal that the parent skill does not already supply.
        - We collude to keep each other in the dark (lines 1987-1994): structural insight about social ecology, not a receiver-side action with its own action and signal. Actionable corollary covered by look-for-pattern-not-counterexample and ask-how-am-i-getting-in-my-own-way.
        - Record yourself (lines 2130-2143): action is concrete (record), but signal-and-failure shape is too tooling-specific to lift cleanly into a receiver-side cognitive skill. Structural insight (anatomical invisibility, external sources are the only way in) folded into separate-impact-from-intent and name-which-mirror-you-need.
        - Focus on change from the inside out (lines 2149-2162): folded into separate-impact-from-intent as the "what to do once the gap is named" portion (talk about the feeling or change the feeling, not just behavior).
        - Have a purpose (lines 2168-2175): scope-setter for the chapter's argument, not a distinct receiver action with its own signal and failure.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter's argument is built around one large frame (the Gap Map) and a sequence of structural insights about why the gap exists (anatomical leaks, the three amplifiers, the colluding-silence ecology) followed by a sequence of practical moves to close it (use the reaction, ask the question, get the second opinion, look for the pattern, change from inside out). The structural insights become parent context for the practical moves; the practical moves become the atomic skills. The Gap Map is the chapter's parent frame and lives in the parent context of every blind-spot skill rather than as its own atomic move. The three amplifiers are united under separate-impact-from-intent because they are three instances of the same asymmetric-story pattern that the impact-vs-intent skill installs. The behavioral-blind-spots category becomes substrate. Record-yourself, the colluding-silence point, and the have-a-purpose scope-setter do not earn standalone skill files.
    - decision: saturated (5 skills)

- Chapter 7: 5. Don't Switchtrack (Disentangle What from Who)
    - what came out: three skills
        - spot-the-switchtrack: the chapter's central diagnostic move. When a feedback exchange is escalating without resolving, ask whether the conversation has quietly split into two topics (the giver's original feedback and your relationship-trigger second topic) using the chapter's vocabulary of six trigger families (skill/judgment, credibility, trust, appreciation, autonomy, acceptance). Folds in all six trigger-type subsections, the silent-switchtrack note, and the four spotting-practice vignettes.
        - signpost-and-track-each-topic: the chapter's prescriptive response to a spotted switchtrack. Step outside the conversation, name both topics out loud using the chapter's signposting template, and propose a sequence using the chapter's two-factor decision rule (default to the giver's topic, override only when your trigger is loud enough that you would not actually take in their topic). Captures Ella's worked case and Louie's hypothetical "Take Two" line.
        - listen-for-the-issue-beneath-the-coaching: the chapter's third move, distinct from switchtrack-spotting and signposting. The inverse case: the giver has packaged a relationship concern as coaching, and the receiver who stays on the surface coaching topic is on a topic that was never the real one. Captures the four "might mean" diagnostic pairs, the chapter's check-question ("Are we on the same track? What is the real topic here?"), and the mother-and-marriage worked sequence with the "what are you worried about?" probe.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the six relationship-trigger types as a typology (skill/judgment, credibility, trust, appreciation, autonomy, acceptance): folded into spot-the-switchtrack as the diagnostic vocabulary the spotter uses to name the second topic. As its own skill the action would be pure typology with no distinct procedural move beyond identify-which-trigger-is-firing's framework-level diagnosis at higher resolution.
        - separate-trust-from-content (the trust subsection's prescription): folded into spot-the-switchtrack and signpost-and-track-each-topic as one named topic-pair (trust vs. content). Same pattern for separate-skill-or-judgment-from-content and separate-credibility-from-content: each is the parent diagnostic and signposting move applied to a specific topic-pair, not a structurally distinct move.
        - surprise players (strangers, people you find difficult): folded into ask-how-am-i-getting-in-my-own-way (chapter 6) as the source-selection half. The chapter is making a where-to-look point, structurally identical to the chapter-6 eliciting-question skill with a specific source designation. Cross-reference to be added in the cross-ref pass.
        - acceptance-as-immunity ("accept me as I am" as escape hatch): dropped because the move is a one-liner already covered by name-both-needs (chapter 2) plus separate-impact-from-intent (chapter 6).
        - appreciation-trigger-as-swift-reversal: dropped as descriptive without a distinct receiver action; the move it implies is generic switchtrack-handling.
        - autonomy-as-control-not-content: dropped as the same generic switchtrack move applied to a specific topic-pair (boundary vs. content).
        - Louie-and-Kim Take Two: dropped as the chapter's synthesis demonstration; used as worked-example source for spot-the-switchtrack and signpost-and-track-each-topic.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter's argument is built around one diagnostic (the switchtrack), one response (signposting), and one inverse case (advice as relationship-concern-in-disguise). Each earns a skill. The chapter spends most of its middle on the typology of relationship triggers (six varieties across two families), but the typology resolves to the same procedural move regardless of which type is firing, so it becomes the diagnostic vocabulary inside spot-the-switchtrack rather than its own atomic skill. The "surprise players" sidebar is a blind-spot point that the chapter-6 eliciting-question skill already handles, gaining a who-to-ask refinement. The acceptance and appreciation and autonomy subsections each give a one-liner that collapses into the parent procedural moves. The Louie/Kim Take-Two scene is synthesis demonstration.
    - decision: saturated (3 skills)

- Chapter 8: 6. Identify the Relationship System (Take Three Steps Back)
    - what came out: four skills
        - take-three-steps-back: the chapter's meta-framework. When feedback arrives and the blame frame is stuck (each person sees the other's contribution clearly and not their own), step back through three views of the relationship system. One step: you+me intersections (the specific combination of tendencies that produces the downward spiral). Two steps: role clashes (structural tug-of-war that would exist between any two people in these roles, regardless of character). Three steps: big picture (other players, processes, policies, physical environment, timing, coping strategies). Folds in the Kenzie classroom worked example across all three views, the Me+Everybody pattern (when one person changes, multiple systems improve), and the systems-as-source-of-structural-change point (shift roles, change processes, change environment rather than demanding personality change).
        - spot-the-shifter-or-absorber-pattern: names the two dysfunctional accountability profiles the chapter introduces under "It Helps Correct Our Tendency to Shift or Absorb." Absorbers accept all blame quickly, cut conversations short, build private resentment, and in extremis stay in abusive situations. Shifters deflect all blame to external causes, feel victimized, and remain impenetrable to feedback. The skill installs the diagnostic for naming which pattern is running, in yourself or in the conversation, so it can be interrupted.
        - take-responsibility-first-then-introduce-the-system: the sequencing rule for when the receiver wants to name the system. Two messages (I take responsibility for my part; we are both contributing) must be sent, but in order. Message one must be fully delivered and settled before message two is attempted. If message two arrives before message one is settled, the giver hears the whole move as sophisticated deflection. Also folds in the vocabulary caution: avoid "relationship system" language, which signals theory rather than honesty.
        - ask-what-would-help-you-change: for when the giver is stuck in "this is all about you" and cannot hear message two. Instead of demanding they acknowledge their contribution, describe specifically what they could do differently that would help the receiver change. Framed legitimately as serving the receiver's change rather than as critique of the giver. Gil's script as the model: name the reaction, own that it is out of proportion, name what triggers it, ask for the specific behavior change that would help.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the three systems insights (each of us is part of the problem; each of us sees only the other's contribution; the chapter's two formal propositions): parent-frame framing, not distinct receiver actions. They underlie take-three-steps-back but do not generate their own skill with a distinct signal and action.
        - the three benefits of systems thinking (more accurate, reduces judgment, enhances accountability): framing and motivation for the system view; the actionable corollaries are already in take-three-steps-back and spot-the-shifter-or-absorber-pattern.
        - fixes that fail (the Benny/Alice/Vince/board case): illustrative of the cost of single-component fixes in a system; the diagnostic and remedy are already in take-three-steps-back and the Benny/Alice case is used as the worked micro-example in spot-the-shifter-or-absorber-pattern.
        - "be on the lookout" (attend to silent "not my fault" thoughts as system signals): a disposition note, not a distinct move; the move it implies is take-three-steps-back with those thoughts as the triggering signal. Folded into take-three-steps-back's "when to reach for this" section.
        - look for themes: Me + Everybody intersection: a diagnostic refinement within the take-three-steps-back framework (one step back, iterating over multiple people); not a structurally distinct move. Folded into take-three-steps-back under the Me+Everybody point.
        - use the system to support change (shift roles, change processes, change environment): a corollary and closing point of take-three-steps-back; folded into that skill rather than promoted separately.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter's argument is built as a sequence of conceptual frames (systems insights), a three-step diagnostic tool, two accountability profiles, and a set of conversation moves. The three conceptual frames are parent context for the tool and not receiver actions. The three benefits are motivation for the tool. The two accountability profiles earn one combined skill because the diagnostic move is the same (name the pattern; interrupt it) and the chapter presents them as a pair. The conversation moves (take responsibility, sequence your messages, ask what would help you change) are three structurally distinct moves that each earn a skill. The "be on the lookout" note and the "look for themes" refinement are embedded as conditions in take-three-steps-back rather than promoted, because they do not have distinct actions or failure modes beyond what the parent skill already supplies.
    - decision: saturated (4 skills)

- Chapter 9: 7. Learn How Wiring and Temperament Affect Your Story
    - what came out: two skills
        - understand-your-wiring-profile: the chapter's first section. Name your profile on three variables (baseline, swing, sustain/recovery) so that unusually strong or weak emotional reactions to feedback are attributed to the nervous system's built-in configuration rather than to the content of the feedback. Folds in the Krista/Alita contrast as the worked cases, the "bad is stronger than good" negativity-bias substrate, and the positive-sustain extension technique (recalling positive feedback to maintain the neural circuit). The liberation framing (wiring is not judgment-worthy, not fixed, not destiny) is the parent context rather than a separate action.
        - notice-the-distortion-type: the chapter's second section. When a story about feedback is escalating past what the feedback literally said, name which of the three distortion patterns is running: Google bias (past is flooded with confirming failures), flooding (one specific feedback overflows into all-or-nothing present self-image), or forever bias / snowballing (current bad feeling projected as permanent or as the first domino in a chain of disasters). The remedies are deferred to chapter 10; this skill installs the diagnostic step that must precede dismantling.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the neuroscience substrate (amygdala, prefrontal cortex right-vs-left, nucleus accumbens): explanatory context for why wiring differences produce different reactions; no separate receiver action with its own signal and failure mode. Folded into understand-your-wiring-profile as background.
        - "bad is stronger than good" (negativity bias): a finding that explains the asymmetry, not a distinct receiver action; absorbed as context into understand-your-wiring-profile.
        - the 50-40-10 formula: motivational framing for the 40% interpretive zone; the actual interpretation moves are in chapters 10-11. Not a separate action.
        - the thoughts-feelings interplay / soundtrack metaphor: parent context for notice-the-distortion-type; explains the mechanism but not the diagnostic step. Folded into the distortion skill's framing.
        - the four sustain/recovery combinations (chart): taxonomy that extends the three variables into four cases; descriptive, no new action. Absorbed into understand-your-wiring-profile.
        - "wiring is not fixed" / neuroplasticity: normative claim and motivation; no distinct action. Folded into understand-your-wiring-profile's liberation framing.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter has two purposes. The first is to explain wiring differences; the explanation yields one diagnostic skill (understand-your-wiring-profile) and the rest is substrate. The second is to identify how emotions distort stories; the identification yields one diagnostic skill (notice-the-distortion-type) and the rest is mechanism. The neuroscience sections (amygdala, the four combination chart, neuroplasticity) are the explanatory scaffold for these two skills, not independent actions. The remedies for distorted thinking are explicitly deferred to chapter 10, which means chapter 9's distortion content stops at the diagnostic.
    - decision: saturated (2 skills)

- Chapter 10: 8. Dismantle Distortions (See Feedback at "Actual Size")
    - what came out: five skills
        - know-your-feedback-footprint: name your reactive behavioral patterns before a feedback conversation (your footprint), inoculate yourself by pre-experiencing the worst-case emotionally while balanced, and notice the footprint activating during the conversation so you can name it to yourself. The chapter's mechanism: naming the reaction activates the calming left prefrontal cortex and creates enough distance for the reaction to pass rather than escalate.
        - separate-feeling-story-feedback: three-question move to pull apart the merged response to feedback. Question 1: what do I feel (name and physically describe the emotion). Question 2: what is the story I am telling, and inside it, what is the threat. Question 3: what was the actual feedback (exact words, without the story). Also folds in "shadowboxing with the past" (last straw dynamics and open wounds that earlier accumulated comments have created), used as the depth-probe for the threat question.
        - contain-the-story: restore the three "laws of physics for stories" (time, specificity, people) that strong feelings cause the receiver to violate. Three tools: Feedback Containment Chart (what this IS about vs. what it is NOT about), Balancing Picture (visual representation of the proportion of positive-to-negative feedback), and Right-size the future consequences (distinguish will-happen from might-happen consequences; apply Gilbert's finding that people consistently overestimate how awful they will feel and how long they will feel awful).
        - change-your-vantage-point: three perspective-shift techniques for when the distorted story cannot be corrected from inside it. Observer perspective (give yourself the advice you would give your sister in the same situation). Future vantage (look back on today from 20 or 40 years hence). Cast the comedy (find the gallows humor, which activates the positive left prefrontal cortex and disrupts the amygdala's alarm signals).
        - accept-feedback-as-input-not-imprint: accept that you cannot control how others see you and stop investing energy in changing their view. Others' views are input (examinable, contextualizable, decidable) not imprint (permanent and defining). Folds in the "have compassion for them" technique: de-personalize an unfair verdict by locating the wound the other person is operating from.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the Seth story: worked synthesis example for know-your-feedback-footprint and separate-feeling-story-feedback; used as the micro-example for both.
        - "our stories shadowbox with the past" / last straw / open wounds: diagnostic insight folded into separate-feeling-story-feedback as the depth-probe for the story-and-threat question. Not a separate skill because the action (ask about older material) is a step inside the strand-separation move.
        - "when life comes down hard" / drowning / ask for support: clinical section for people in genuine depression or crisis. The move (reach out for help, find supportive mirrors) is not feedback-specific; it is general mental health guidance. The skill framework is not the right instrument for clinical intervention. Not extracted.
        - the supportive-mirrors framing: a useful formulation within the "ask for support" section, but it applies at the drowning end of the spectrum rather than at the distortion-dismantling end. Left with the drowning section.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter has five numbered strategies, each of which earns a skill. The Seth story and the shadowboxing insight are synthesis/substrate for the skills. The drowning/support section operates in a different register (clinical rather than distortion-dismantling) and does not produce a skill with the same signal-and-failure-mode structure as the five strategies.
    - decision: saturated (5 skills)

- Chapter 12: 10. How Good Do I Have to Be? (Draw Boundaries When Enough Is Enough)
    - what came out: three skills
        - diagnose-and-name-the-boundary: combines the two diagnostic subsections of the chapter. Six questions for determining whether a boundary is needed (character attack vs. behavior feedback, unrelenting feedback, always-one-more-demand pattern, relationship-hostage dynamic, threats disguised as warnings, always-you-who-changes, and feelings-legitimacy criterion). Three-type taxonomy for naming which boundary to set (I may not take it / not right now / stop or I'll leave). The chapter presents these as sequential: first determine if a boundary is needed, then name the type.
        - set-the-boundary-clearly: the procedural how-to for the boundary-setting conversation. Be transparent (tell them out loud), be firm and appreciative simultaneously, redirect coaching energy to a corner of the acre you'd welcome, use "and" not "but" (the And Stance), be specific about the request + time frame + assent, describe consequences as warnings not threats.
        - mitigate-when-not-changing: the duty to mitigate after refusing feedback. Ask about the impact on affected parties, coach them to deal with the unchanged you (give them specific tools), and problem-solve together to design a modified arrangement. The chapter frames this as the counterpart to setting boundaries: if you are keeping feedback out, you owe those affected the work of reducing the cost of your decision on them.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the three common relationship patterns (constant critic, hate-love-hate, renovation relationship): worked examples that illustrate the diagnostic questions in context. Used as micro-examples in diagnose-and-name-the-boundary. Not separate skills because they do not introduce new moves beyond the six diagnostic questions.
        - Martin's development plan opening story: framing/motivation for the chapter; no action.
        - Anne Lamott's emotional-acre passage: framing/motivation for the right to draw limits; no action.
        - "but wait, does that mean?" nuance: a clarification (wanting your partner to change is fine if they want it too); absorbed as a condition note in the chapter's argument, not a separate action.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter has three structural sections (diagnose whether needed + name type / how to set it / duty to mitigate). Each section earns a skill. The relationship pattern case studies and the framing passages are substrate for the diagnostic skill. The clarification nuance is a scope note rather than a distinct move.
    - decision: saturated (3 skills)

- Chapter 13: 11. Navigate the Conversation
    - what came out: six skills
        - align-on-conversation-purpose: at the opening, clarify three questions before engaging with content: is this feedback and if so what kind, who decides, is it final or negotiable. Also: you can influence the frame and agenda regardless of how the giver started; this is a process move about the conversation's structure, not its substance. Folds in the Gottman research (harsh first three minutes predict negative outcome 96% of the time).
        - negotiate-your-internal-voice: rather than suppressing the internal voice during feedback, give it attention (it quiets when heard), identify its trigger pattern (truth/relationship/identity), and negotiate it toward curiosity by asking "what might be right about what they're saying?" Also folds in the hot-inquiry warning: when your questions become heated assertions, stop inquiring and assert clearly instead.
        - assert-as-left-out: reframe assertion from "I'm right" to "here's the missing piece." You are adding your data/interpretations/feelings as puzzle pieces, not replacing the giver's truth with yours. "I disagree with that advice" rather than "that advice is wrong." Three trigger-specific assertion pitfalls and their fixes (truth: "wrong" vs. "I disagree"; relationship: "self-centered jerk" vs. two-topic naming; identity: "I'm hopeless" collapse vs. transparent overwhelm + time request).
        - make-a-process-move: step outside the conversation, diagnose what is stuck (both arguing without listening, two tangled topics, perspective-as-truth fight, emotional flooding, deadlock), describe it explicitly, and propose a next step or invite joint problem-solving. The chapter's five worked examples cover the five most common stuck patterns.
        - dig-for-interests-then-generate-options: move from positions (what the giver says should change) to interests (what they are actually trying to accomplish). Three interest buckets: helping you, helping themselves/the relationship, helping others/the organization. Once interests are identified, generate options that address them. Earl's case as the worked example (clean up appearance → families feel comfortable → introduce him as a banjo player).
        - close-with-commitment: before parting, name what was agreed and what each party will do next. Does not require agreeing with the feedback or promising to change; can commit to gathering more information, returning to the conversation, or stating which parts of the feedback will not be taken. Four types of commitment: action plans, benchmarks and consequences, procedural contracts, new strategies.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the keyframes/tweening metaphor: framing for the chapter; no skill.
        - the "putting it all together" performance rating worked example (version four): synthesis demonstration of all six skills working together; used as micro-example in align-on-conversation-purpose and assert-as-left-out.
        - versions one through three of the performance rating conversation: failure-mode illustrations for assert-as-left-out and align-on-conversation-purpose; not separate skills.
        - the empathy-shutdown neuroscience (Singer/mirror neurons): explanatory substrate for why listening during triggered feedback is not natural; folded into negotiate-your-internal-voice.
        - the four-category listening table (trigger patterns with what to listen for and questions to ask): a reference tool, not a separate action; folded into negotiate-your-internal-voice.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter has a named open-body-close structure. The open produces one skill (align-on-conversation-purpose). The body has four named skills (listening, asserting, process moves, problem solving), each earning one skill. The close produces one skill. The worked conversations and the neuroscience are substrate for these six skills.
    - decision: saturated (6 skills)

- Chapter 11: 9. Cultivate a Growth Identity (Sort Toward Coaching)
    - what came out: five skills
        - embrace-identity-nuance: the first identity shift. When feedback challenges a core identity label (good son, fair person, strong leader), the all-or-nothing structure of the label forces an unwinnable choice between exaggerating the feedback (I'm nothing) and denying it (I'm all). The skill replaces the binary label with a complex self-description: "I care deeply about X, there are examples of my living up to it, and some of my falling short." Also folds in the three things to accept about yourself from the book (you will make mistakes, you have complex intentions, you have contributed to the problem) as the three specific nuances to practice acknowledging.
        - adopt-growth-mindset-for-feedback: the second identity shift. Drawing on Dweck's research, treats traits and abilities as growable rather than fixed. Under a fixed mindset, feedback is a verdict; under a growth mindset, feedback is information about where you are on a learning curve. The Testing Room vs. Learning Room frame. Growth-mindset people in the EEG study listened to the right answers after getting something wrong; fixed-mindset people stopped listening.
        - sort-toward-coaching: the first growth-identity practice. Default to sorting feedback into the coaching bin rather than the evaluation bin. The identity reaction is triggered by evaluation, not coaching; sorting toward coaching reduces the identity trigger and makes learning available. Includes the sorting exercise (imagine the feedback as evaluation; now imagine it as coaching) and the harder case (when coaching and evaluation are tangled, ask what the giver wants and find the coaching at the core).
        - unpack-judgment-from-evaluation: the second growth-identity practice. When feedback is genuinely evaluative and cannot be sorted as coaching, break it into assessment (where do I stand, the measurement), consequences (what happens as a result, certain vs. speculative), and judgment (the story the evaluator tells about the assessment and its consequences). Identity is most triggered by judgment. Locating the trigger in one component allows the other two to be handled without the same identity load.
        - give-yourself-a-second-score: the third growth-identity practice. After any negative first score, earn a second score for how you handle the first. Make the second score part of your identity ("I take an honest shot at figuring out what there is to learn"). The first score is what happened; the second score is available regardless. Handling it well is not denying pain but facing it head-on.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - "you've been complicated all along" / the all-or-nothing binary toggle narrative: parent frame for embrace-identity-nuance; folded into that skill as background and motivation.
        - the chapter's conceptual argument for identity nuance (the care-facility narrator's worked case): used as the worked micro-example for embrace-identity-nuance.
        - "but aren't some traits fixed?" section: an objection to the growth mindset with the book's answer; folds into adopt-growth-mindset-for-feedback as context.
        - the framing-matters study (fifth graders praised for smarts vs. effort): evidence for the growth-mindset shift; folded into adopt-growth-mindset-for-feedback.
        - simple labels serve a useful function: context establishing why people hold them; no separate action.
    - why those did not make it: the chapter has two conceptual shifts and three named practices. Each shift earns a skill. Each practice earns a skill. The supporting argumentation, the worked cases (narrator/Rita, puzzles research), and the framing study are all substrate for those five skills. Nothing in the supporting argumentation has a distinct action or failure mode that the five skills do not already cover.
    - decision: saturated (5 skills)

- Chapter 16: Back Matter (Acknowledgments, Notes, About the Authors, Road Map)
    - what came out: nothing
    - why: bibliographic and referential back matter; no authorial argument or teaching content.
    - decision: saturated (0 skills, vacuously)

- Chapter 15: 13. Pull Together (Feedback in Organizations)
    - what came out: nothing
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - "don't just trumpet benefits, explain tradeoffs" / Jane's exco strategy: guidance for HR/leadership presenting systems; not a receiver-side action.
