    - why those did not make it: this chapter is addressed primarily to leaders, HR, and feedback givers. Its receiver-side content (Sara's case, closing section) is either a worked example for existing skills or a restatement of the book's core thesis. No new receiver-side action with a distinct signal, failure mode, and procedure that is not already covered.
    - decision: saturated (0 skills, vacuously)

- Chapter 14: 12. Get Going (Five Ways to Take Action)
    - what came out: five skills
        - ask-for-one-thing-and-find-the-theme: three techniques for soliciting focused feedback. (1) Name one thing: ask "what's one thing you see me doing that gets in my own way?" rather than the vague "any feedback?", to get the giver to prioritize. (2) Listen for themes: go to 3-5 people with the one-thing question, look for what recurs across sources. (3) Ask what matters to them: "what's one thing I could change that would make a difference to you?" to surface the giver's actual concern. Folds in the cookie-and-radish research (willpower for change is a limited resource).
        - try-small-experiments: treat uncertain feedback as an experiment rather than a decision. Reframe from all-and-always to some-and-sometimes. Try it on (mental simulation: inhabit the possibility the feedback is true) and try it out (real-world time-limited test). Folds in Emily, Harpreet, and Gawande.
        - precommit-to-riding-the-j-curve: name the J curve (worse before better), design precommitment strategies before the change starts. Increase appeal (make it social, keep score) or increase cost of not changing (tie yourself to the mast). Commit to a specific duration. Folds in Sunday Night vs. Monday Morning two-decision-maker framing.
        - coach-your-coach: tell the feedback giver how to work with you more effectively. Share footprint, current growth areas, learning preferences. For formal relationships: discuss roles, mutual expectations, and what the coach finds challenging. Frame in terms of current job effectiveness in hierarchy.
        - shift-to-honest-mirror: explicitly request a supportive mirror to shift to honest-mirror mode. Use the two-column technique: what's wrong with the feedback / what might be right. Goal is learning, not reaching a verdict on who was right.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - invite-them-in coda (four relationship transformation stories): inspiring narratives; no distinct procedural move beyond the honest-mirror shift.
        - "don't become a gimme-feedback fanatic": scope note, no distinct action.
        - reverse mentor / when the person being coached is the boss: sub-case of coach-your-coach.
    - why those did not make it: five named sections; the first aggregates three techniques; the invite-them-in section is primarily narrative with one extractable technique (honest-mirror shift). Coda and scope notes are substrate.
    - decision: saturated (5 skills)
